If using a third party library is an option, there is [jOOU][2] (a spin off library from [jOOQ][1]), which offers wrapper types for unsigned integer numbers in Java. That&#39;s not exactly the same thing as having primitive type (and thus byte code) support for unsigned types, but perhaps it&#39;s still good enough for your use-case.

    import static org.joou.Unsigned.*;
    
    // and then...
    UByte    b = ubyte(1);
    UShort   s = ushort(1);
    UInteger i = uint(1);
    ULong    l = ulong(1);

All of these types extend `java.lang.Number` and can be converted into higher-order primitive types and `BigInteger`. In your case, earlier versions of jOOU simply stored the unsigned long value in a `BigInteger`. Version 0.9.3 does some cool bit shifting to fit the value in an ordinary `long`.

(Disclaimer: I work for the company behind these libraries)

  [1]: http://www.jooq.org
  [2]: https://github.com/jOOQ/jOOU

